{
  "doc_id": "55495",
  "text": "Cell movement is an integral part of metastasis. Migration is regulated by numerous chemokines, cytokines, and growth factors that in general promote cell migration by causing changes in the cytoskeletal structure and cell adhesion. When added to cells in culture, WNT5A inhibits migration in part by increasing adhesion [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Drugs that target migration of tumor cells could be used to combat metastatic disease. Recently, a WNT5A peptide agonist, FOXY-5 was shown to inhibit breast cancer metastasis in an in vivo mouse model [CITATION_3] . Although WNT5A is known to inhibit migration in breast cancer cell lines, the consequences of WNT5A expression on specific migration associated gene targets are not known.",
